05847nam a22008655i 9780812293906DE-B159720210830012106.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210830t20172017pau    fo  d z      eng d  a97808122939067 a10.9783/97808122939062doi  a(DE-B1597)481221  a(OCoLC)992454586  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  apaucUS-PA 4aB753.F34bO79 2017eb 7aPOL0100002bisacsh04a320.0922231 aOrwin, Alexander, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aRedefining the Muslim Community :bEthnicity, Religion, and Politics in the Thought of Alfarabi /cAlexander Orwin. 1aPhiladelphia : bUniversity of Pennsylvania Press, c[2017] 4c©2017  a1 online resource (264 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tA Note on Citations and Abbreviations -- tIntroduction. Alfarabi and the Question of the Umma (Nation) -- tChapter 1. The Nation in Plato and Aristotle: An Obstacle to Virtuous Rule -- tChapter 2. From Speechlessness to Civilization: The Evolution of the Umma -- tChapter 3. Philosophy and the Umma: An Uneasy Coexistence -- tChapter 4. Another Kind of Umma: The Origin of the Islamic Umma -- tChapter 5. The Mission of the Virtuous Umma: Ethnic Accommodation Within Islam -- tChapter 6. Between City and Empire: The Political Significance of the Umma -- tChapter 7. The Umma Among the Ignorant Associations: Nationalism and the Threat of War -- tConclusion. The Intermediate Association -- tNotes -- tWorks Cited -- tIndex of Proper Names -- tIndex of Subjects -- tAcknowledgments0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aWriting in the cosmopolitan metropolis of Baghdad, Alfarabi (870-950) is unique in the history of premodern political philosophy for his extensive discussion of the nation, or Umma in Arabic. The term Umma may be traced back to the Qur'ān and signifies, then and now, both the Islamic religious community as a whole and the various ethnic nations of which that community is composed, such as the Turks, Persians, and Arabs. Examining Alfarabi's political writings as well as parts of his logical commentaries, his book on music, and other treatises, Alexander Orwin contends that the connections and tensions between ethnic and religious Ummas explored by Alfarabi in his time persist today in the ongoing political and cultural disputes among the various nationalities within Islam.According to Orwin, Alfarabi strove to recast the Islamic Umma as a community in both a religious and cultural sense, encompassing art and poetry as well as law and piety. By proposing to acknowledge and accommodate diverse Ummas rather than ignoring or suppressing them, Alfarabi anticipated the contemporary concept of "Islamic civilization," which emphasizes culture at least as much as religion. Enlisting language experts, jurists, theologians, artists, and rulers in his philosophic enterprise, Alfarabi argued for a new Umma that would be less rigid and more creative than the Muslim community as it has often been understood, and therefore less inclined to force disparate ethnic and religious communities into a single mold. Redefining the Muslim Community demonstrates how Alfarabi's judicious combination of cultural pluralism, religious flexibility, and political prudence could provide a blueprint for reducing communal strife in a region that continues to be plagued by it today.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aEthnicityxPolitical aspects. 0aIslam and state. 0aIslamic philosophy. 0aPhilosophy, Medieval. 0aUmmah (Islam). 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / History & Theory.2bisacsh  aAfrican Studies.  aAsian Studies.  aMiddle Eastern Studies.  aPhilosophy.  aPolitical Science.  aPublic Policy.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe Gr